Here is "poste," and that doesn't make any

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:05.570
sense.

00:05:05.570 --> 00:05:11.550
So something is broken, and to explain why this is happening

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:15.110
, I have to talk about internationalization.

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:18.450
By the way, did you ever notice that there were 18

00:05:18.450 --> 00:05:19.120
characters?

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:24.640
That's why we write it like that everywhere.

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:27.720
Actually, a lot of people don't know that, and

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:30.610
it's a weird way of doing an acronym, but yeah

00:05:30.610 --> 00:05:30.720
.

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:37.840
There are two main ways of organizing strings, translations.

00:05:37.840 --> 00:05:42.290
In a project, you can either decide a reference language.

00:05:42.290 --> 00:05:45.400
Not surprisingly, most of the time it's English.

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:51.110
And every word that is shown to the users is directly written

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:53.520
in that reference language in the source code.

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:57.860
And then internationalization libraries, and check out if there are

00:05:57.860 --> 00:06:01.120
any translations for those words in a translation file, and swap

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:01.360
those.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:07.260
But you have also another strategy that is the hierarchical ident

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:09.520
ifiers.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:10.080
You got it.

00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:15.030
And basically, you treat all the words shown on the screen

00:06:15.330 --> 00:06:20.640
as external data that you reference using symbolic keys like those.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:26.560
The benefit of this approach is that those identifiers are clear

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:29.840
for translators, because we have context.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:34.060
And you can edit the text shown to users even in your

00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:35.600
own language.

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:40.930
So if you want to change what we also call microcop

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:44.230
y, the word that you use for the users, even

00:06:44.230 --> 00:06:47.050
in English, you can do so without changing the source code

00:06:47.050 --> 00:06:49.350
, which is something kind of nice.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:55.780
And it's also cool because in a thinking way, English

00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:57.680
is just another language.

00:06:57.680 --> 00:06:59.310
It's not the reference language.

00:06:59.310 --> 00:07:01.520
So that's a cool way to do that.

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:03.840
But blue sky shows the former.

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:06.050
And honestly, I do understand that.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:10.960
Because let's be honest, most English speaking developers just want

00:07:10.960 --> 00:07:12.710
to iterate very quickly.

00:07:12.710 --> 00:07:16.790
And they just slap the translation after the fact.

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:19.440
And so yeah, this shows the first strategy.

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:21.650
And it's very common.

00:07:21.650 --> 00:07:22.880
And honestly, it works.

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:28.080
So and this is one of the two slides with code on

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:28.880
it.

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:35.040
We just slap the trends tag into that.

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:39.520
And like lives, these trends tags matters a lot.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:43.380
It's a way for the international library to do its job

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:47.510
and go fetch your actual translation for that string here post.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:52.720
So now that you know a little bit more about internationalization

00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:54.000
, how can we fix this problem?

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.400
Well, actually, it's quite simple.

00:07:56.660 --> 00:08:02.210
And even if we have to do something on the source code

00:08:02.210 --> 00:08:05.740
, of course, we just have to add context tags,

00:08:05.740 --> 00:08:10.800
basically attaching some context to each of these strings.

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:15.430
The first one is basically, you know, standard unknown.

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:17.280
The second one, an action verb.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:21.860
And in the code, the second side, we simply have

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:25.790
to add context equal description, because post is a description of

00:08:25.790 --> 00:08:27.040
the thing, not an action.

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:32.320
As soon as we do that, the localization catalog updates

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:33.910
, and we have two separate entries.

00:08:33.910 --> 00:08:36.420
And I can simply translate the second one and not the first

00:08:36.490 --> 00:08:36.880
one.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:41.490
And ta-da, everything is translated correctly.

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:43.200
Success.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:46.110
So the thing that I want you to remember for this first

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:48.080
example is context is everything.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:51.390
Something that we know, but it's important to, you

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:53.120
know, to say again.

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:57.200
And you have to be ready to hear the demands of your

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:00.240
translators to add context tags if you use the first strategy

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:00.400
.

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:03.040
If you use the second, normally, you shouldn't have

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:06.000
to do that, because it's already in the identifier.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.560
And to their credits, the Blue Sky team always accepted our

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:14.060
pull request very quickly to add context tags.

00:09:14.060 --> 00:09:15.590
So that's awesome.

00:09:15.590 --> 00:09:17.680
And I thank them for that.

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:21.520
So context is everything.

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:26.630
Let's get to the next one, "abonner"

00:09:26.740 --> 00:09:28.080
with those weird points.

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:32.320
And you will understand why they are there.

00:09:32.330 --> 00:09:35.190
They are weird dots.

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:39.890
But first, let me tell you a story that starts with

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:41.440
a GitHub issue.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:45.970
This GitHub issue created by Fenarin Arsat is quite

00:09:45.970 --> 00:09:46.560
simple.

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:49.680
Make the French translation gender neutral.

00:09:49.680 --> 00:09:55.120
And as I said, the current French translation does not follow

00:09:55.120 --> 00:09:59.080
the current recommendation for non-sexist and more inclusive French

00:09:59.080 --> 00:09:59.680
forms.

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:02.820
To explain what he's talking about, I have to explain

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:04.160
a few things about French.

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:08.590
So please bear with me while I will try to offer you

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:10.120
some French 101 lesson.

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:12.480
I know you understand why it may take a long time.

00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:16.720
This is a hat.

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:20.650
In French, we would translate it as "un chape

00:10:20.650 --> 00:10:20.880
au".

00:10:21.060 --> 00:10:23.010
This is a tulip.

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:27.630
In French, "une tulip", "une tulip

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:28.080
".

00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:29.200
Yeah.

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:31.240
Did you notice, "une tulip", it's a

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:32.320
feminine word.

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:35.600
In French, everything is gendered.

00:10:35.600 --> 00:10:38.080
We chose a gender for everything.

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:41.440
And there is an aesthetics here, but honestly, nearly everything

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:43.840
has gendered has gendered in French, even for brand

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:44.320
new words.

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:49.100
So some examples of gendered things, so you understand the

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:50.800
mess that it can become.

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:52.370
This is a chair.

00:10:52.630 --> 00:10:56.480
It's feminine, "une chaise".

00:10:56.480 --> 00:10:58.320
This is a seat.

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:02.290
It's masculine, "un siège".

00:11:02.290 --> 00:11:03.800
This is a shoe.

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:06.960
It's feminine, "une chaise".

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:08.640
This is a finger.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:11.260
It's masculine, it's a finger.

00:11:11.300 --> 00:11:14.720
But it gets even weirder because here is Canada.

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:17.760
It's masculine for some reason.

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:19.670
But here is Poland.

00:11:19.670 --> 00:11:22.640
It's feminine for some reason.

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:24.960
Strength is feminine.

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:26.480
La force.

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:29.520
Love is masculine.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:30.480
Un amour.

00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:31.040
Oh la la.

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:35.360
When I say nearly everything, really I mean it.

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:37.800
So, gendering is not optional.

00:11:38.020 --> 00:11:41.200
This is a key thing that you have to remember.

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:44.400
If you say "un tulip" inside a sentence and

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:47.280
you are not a beginner or a tourist, that means that

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:50.290
we have not switched to in the quirks mode, that

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:54.240
we will do some extra mile or, you know, extra

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:57.600
kilometers, as we say, we will offer to correct you

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:01.680
, even verbally, because we will assume that you made an

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:03.810
error or we didn't understand you.

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:05.600
It's like a checksum or CRC.

00:12:05.600 --> 00:12:09.910
So that's not the end of it.

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:12.160
Here is a big hat.

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:14.640
Un grand chapeau.

00:12:15.020 --> 00:12:17.670
Here is a big tulip.

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:20.880
Une grande tulipe.

00:12:20.880 --> 00:12:25.200
In French, we do an accord.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:26.320
This.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:30.000
That means that we do change the form of the adjectives

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.700
that comes with the noun.

00:12:31.700 --> 00:12:34.610
By the way, I learned that it was called a co

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:36.720
-chord in English, but nobody says that, so

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:37.840
we don't care.

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:39.360
Here are two tulips.

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:42.390
Actually, you do a code in English, but only for

00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:42.880
the noun.

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:45.600
And we do it, of course, in French.

00:12:45.600 --> 00:12:49.040
Here is two big tulip.

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:49.680
Tulips.

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:54.160
So, of course, both gender and number are used in

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:55.920
the circle.

00:12:55.920 --> 00:13:01.350
And it also works with people.

00:13:01.350 --> 00:13:03.040
And so, we talked a lot about gender of stuff.

00:13:03.040 --> 00:13:05.960
Because, of course, gender of people also affects the language

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:06.240
.

00:13:06.240 --> 00:13:09.800
Here, an old man, un vieil homme, two

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:10.400
old men.

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:11.680
Oh, did you notice?

00:13:11.680 --> 00:13:13.680
You also do an accord with a weird thing.

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:15.920
It's not only about other languages.

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:17.440
Deux vieux hommes.

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:20.560
Two old women.

00:13:20.560 --> 00:13:22.240
Deux vieilles femmes.

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:26.850
Now, that you have all of that in mind, let

00:13:26.910 --> 00:13:32.330
's take a more complex example so you understand the problem that

00:13:32.330 --> 00:13:33.460
is coming.

00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:35.410
Here is a detective.

00:13:35.410 --> 00:13:39.940
In French, we can translate that to "un inspecteur

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:40.080
".

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:43.470
And the gender is visible because it's "un inspecteur

00:13:43.690 --> 00:13:43.720
".

00:13:43.720 --> 00:13:47.510
Because if it was a female detective, it would be "

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:48.860
une inspectrice".

00:13:48.860 --> 00:13:51.380
As you can see, "une" changed, but also

00:13:51.380 --> 00:13:52.720
"inspectrice".

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:54.800
And that means...

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:57.260
Oh, by the way, we don't know the gender

00:13:57.260 --> 00:13:58.110
of the user.

00:13:58.110 --> 00:14:01.280
So, maybe you can deduce the problem that we can

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:02.480
have at some point.

00:14:02.480 --> 00:14:05.060
But actually, it's not the actual problem that I'm

00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:06.440
talking about right now.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:09.040
But, of course, it also happens.

00:14:09.040 --> 00:14:13.520
When you have two detectives, a duo of detectives

00:14:13.520 --> 00:14:16.720
, one male detective and a female detective.

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:19.340
Together, we call them two detectives.

00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:22.400
Which gender should we use in French for this group?

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:26.740
Well, you will have to use the masculine form.

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:27.600
Deux inspecteur.

00:14:27.600 --> 00:14:28.640
I know.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:32.230
But here's a team with five detectives and four of

00:14:32.230 --> 00:14:34.000
them are female detectives.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.360
How should we translate five detectives in that case?

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:39.760
Masculine again.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:41.750
Cinq inspecteur.

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:45.440
This comes from an old rule we even learned in school,

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:46.600
masculine.

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:47.970
Le masculin l'emporte.

00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:49.550
The masculine takes it all.

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:52.560
As soon as there is one noun subject or part of a

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.440
group that is masculine, we should use the masculine group for

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:56.400
the whole group.

00:14:56.400 --> 00:14:59.100
And let's be honest, this rule sucks.

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:02.600
People try to reason about it, saying that in French,

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:04.570
masculine is a neutral form.

00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:05.620
It's a cop-out.

00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:08.180
Always gendering in masculine...

00:15:08.240 --> 00:15:10.160
in the masculine form, sorry.

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:14.310
The masculine form blocks some young women from projecting themselves to wall

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:17.390
domains, can make them feel non-represented.

00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:20.060
And moreover, that's just unfair in a lot of

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:20.640
ways.

00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:24.770
So, at some point in the 21st century, some

00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:27.800
people got fed up with that and tried to change things by

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:31.730
using something that they called écriture inclusive writing.

00:15:32.180 --> 00:15:35.280
Basically, it's just voluntary using some word, piece of

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:38.200
sentences, and tricks to make sure that we stop excluding women

00:15:38.410 --> 00:15:39.280
from the language.

00:15:39.660 --> 00:15:44.550
So, here are two main strategies that we can use to

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:46.680
implement écriture inclusive.

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:52.620
Either write both masculine and feminine forms every time, in whatever

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:56.640
order, by the way, or merge both forms into a

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:58.140
same word like this.

00:15:58.240 --> 00:16:03.200
And to do that, you use some points médians,

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:06.620
which are basically interpreted, but nobody say that even in English

00:16:06.620 --> 00:16:09.250
, which are basically dots that you place in the middle of

00:16:09.370 --> 00:16:11.090
the vertical height of the line.

00:16:11.090 --> 00:16:14.590
Of course, we could use parenthesis, but then you

00:16:14.590 --> 00:16:17.780
put 50% of the population inside parenthesis.

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:19.670
And so, yeah, that's weird.

00:16:19.670 --> 00:16:21.200
So, we tend not to do that.

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:27.290
Equiture inclusive as a linguistic innovation was fringed

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:30.560
at first, but as time goes by, it became more

00:16:30.560 --> 00:16:33.710
and more common news, especially from companies and agencies, because

00:16:33.710 --> 00:16:36.660
it was easy and efficient way to making clear that you wanted

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:39.760
the situation improving, showing that you cared about the subject of

00:16:39.760 --> 00:16:41.360
gender inclusivity.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:46.860
But then, after a few years, I'd say five

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:50.450
or six years of widespread usage, some right-wing people

00:16:50.450 --> 00:16:53.310
started to ask themselves, you know, this world-rec

00:16:53.310 --> 00:16:56.550
riture inclusive thing, isn't this work?

00:16:56.560 --> 00:17:02.180
I mean, they focused a lot about those points médians

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:04.900
form, they call it something ugly, weird, decad

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:08.270
ent, or whatever, and basically created an equal sign between

00:17:08.370 --> 00:17:11.040
using the point médian and being woke.

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:14.550
It was bullshit, you know, but it's like that

00:17:14.550 --> 00:17:15.840
kind of stuff.

00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:18.100
It's not like this kind of stuff would stop them.

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:19.760
It's perfect scapegoat for them.

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:24.240
So, of course, they started coming to the Blue Sky

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:28.910
repository, complaining about using politically-sided language, just because

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:32.920
we followed a somewhat common new practice of caring about inclusivity

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:33.120
.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:36.310
So, from there, what should we do?

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:41.430
Well, actually, I thought about that before they even complained

00:17:41.430 --> 00:17:45.030
, and I trained myself to mainly use a long way of

00:17:45.030 --> 00:17:51.420
doing écriture inclusive by both writing the feminine and masculine forms

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:52.080
.

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:57.490
And then, if and only if we have very little room

00:17:57.490 --> 00:18:00.390
for the translated version, then at the last resort, using

00:18:00.610 --> 00:18:03.190
point médian short form, and it's what we did

00:18:03.190 --> 00:18:05.950
for Abonnez, by the way, the title example

00:18:05.950 --> 00:18:06.950
that I used.

00:18:06.950 --> 00:18:11.090
But we have some trick up our sleeves to make it better

00:18:11.090 --> 00:18:11.360
.

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:13.520
And to be fair, I lied to you.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:14.240
I'm sorry.

00:18:14.240 --> 00:18:14.960
By omission.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:15.920
I'd say.

00:18:15.920 --> 00:18:21.280
What if there were words that shared the same form in both

00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:21.680
tenders?

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:25.520
That's why I use detective as an example.

00:18:25.570 --> 00:18:30.830
A detective can also be translated in French as "un detective

00:18:30.830 --> 00:18:35.380
" and a female detective as "un detective".

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:36.080
Perfect!

00:18:36.770 --> 00:18:40.370
Those words that can be written the same in both masculine and

00:18:40.370 --> 00:18:43.600
feminine form are called "épicenne" words, and

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:46.580
they're awesome for us, because they basically solve the problem

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:47.360
in a very nice way.

00:18:47.700 --> 00:18:49.910
However, they don't always exist.

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:53.340
There are not always synonyms that have this property of

00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:57.120
being "épicenne", including "abonnez",

00:18:57.120 --> 00:18:57.740
by the way.

00:18:57.740 --> 00:18:59.280
That's why I have to use that.

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:02.800
So to recap, going forward when I face this kind of

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.940
puzzle in my translation work, my policy is to try to

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:07.890
find an "épicenne" word, and if I

00:19:07.930 --> 00:19:10.040
can't find one, then to use the expanded version with

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:13.330
both masculine and feminine form, and then, and only when

00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:17.430
space is missing as a last resort using the point médian

00:19:17.430 --> 00:19:17.760
.

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:18.530
And here we have it.

00:19:18.530 --> 00:19:22.000
And by the way, and this, as a conclusion for

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:24.620
this part, here is what Dan Abramoff, that

00:19:24.620 --> 00:19:28.560
at that time, part of the Blue Sky team posted before

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:31.060
closing that pull request that wanted to revert the work that

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:32.800
we did on gender-neutral language.

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:36.880
It was very validating to see part of the Blue Sky

00:19:36.880 --> 00:19:41.190
team officially recognizing the work we did, the balance we tried

00:19:41.190 --> 00:19:45.760
to find by not using the somewhat controversial to the far right

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:49.110
, new forms where we could, and more of the pragmatic

00:19:49.120 --> 00:19:50.880
approach I tried to follow.

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:53.160
So thank you again, Dan and the Blue Sky team for

00:19:53.160 --> 00:19:54.000
our support.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:00.150
Builders, please support your translators if you are working

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:06.320
with your choices.

00:20:06.320 --> 00:20:08.050
Okay, let's get to the fourth point, and we

00:20:08.050 --> 00:20:10.540
have some short time to go on.

00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:13.280
So it's going way easier now.

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:17.840
But not easier, but quicker to understand.

00:20:17.840 --> 00:20:21.840
So this traduis l'angle d'origine anglais

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:21.840
.

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:26.450
So a very quick, only one size, a short French

00:20:26.450 --> 00:20:28.960
102 session.

00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:32.400
I reassure you, it's very, very quick.

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:33.840
This is the cat.

00:20:33.840 --> 00:20:35.010
It's the cat.

00:20:35.060 --> 00:20:37.010
You would agree, I think.

00:20:37.270 --> 00:20:38.000
It's beautiful.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.800
And in French, we would say le chat.

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:41.720
And this is a tree.

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:43.120
It's such a beautiful tree.

00:20:43.120 --> 00:20:44.400
It's the tree.

00:20:44.650 --> 00:20:49.030
And we would say l'arbre, not le ar

00:20:49.190 --> 00:20:49.990
bre.

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:56.280
Because le arbre would sound weird, we get rid of

00:20:56.280 --> 00:20:58.950
the e and we replace it with a little apostrophe.

00:20:59.040 --> 00:21:02.240
Elysion is not optional.

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:04.430
If you don't do it, we will get back to

00:21:04.430 --> 00:21:07.690
the same, we'll crash in a way, and we

00:21:07.690 --> 00:21:09.740
'll ask you, what did you just say?

00:21:10.020 --> 00:21:12.710
Because we will assume that something went wrong.

00:21:12.720 --> 00:21:14.960
It's like a checksum again.

00:21:14.960 --> 00:21:19.120
So when we get back to translating software, for example,

00:21:19.120 --> 00:21:23.170
if you have a message like "new message from Alexandre

00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:25.780
", in English, it would be translated as "nouve

00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:28.720
au message d'Alexandre" in French, and

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:30.560
not "nouveau message d'Alexandre".

00:21:30.560 --> 00:21:31.840
That wouldn't work.

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:37.340
We are used to software not doing the Elysion stuff

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:37.600
.

00:21:38.450 --> 00:21:43.510
Because it's hard to do it properly.

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.800
There are some letters that only triggers the Elysion in

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:46.590
some cases.

00:21:46.590 --> 00:21:48.450
The Haspiré, if you know French.

00:21:48.470 --> 00:21:52.280
And there are a lot of hard-coded exceptions in

00:21:52.280 --> 00:21:53.600
the language too.

00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:57.600
So yeah, we love exceptions in French.

00:21:57.600 --> 00:22:02.090
So because of that, the internationalization library just don't

00:22:02.180 --> 00:22:02.550
care.

00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:07.750
And there's no standard way of doing it, like we

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:08.560
pull over genders.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:12.360
So yeah, it's perceived as too hard and standard.

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:14.720
So what can we do?

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:17.680
Well, if I take this actual example from the BlueS

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:22.240
ky app to translate a string like translated from English, ideally

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:24.710
, we would write "traduit depuis l'anglais

00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:27.450
", but we can't because it's hard to encode

00:22:27.450 --> 00:22:29.440
that in a translation system.

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:32.260
So we can't do "traduit depuis l'ang

00:22:32.260 --> 00:22:34.550
lais" because it will sound like that.

00:22:34.690 --> 00:22:36.700
And we can't do "traduit depuis l'ang

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:37.200
lais" either.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:42.400
So we have to do workarounds like "traduit

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:46.000
originelle en anglais", literally translated originally in English

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:46.000
.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.500
Or because "en" doesn't have this Elysion

00:22:49.570 --> 00:22:50.300
stuff.

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:51.920
So we don't care.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:52.320
It works.

00:22:52.320 --> 00:22:56.510
Actually, I didn't use that one, but an even

00:22:56.530 --> 00:22:59.520
clearer one, because in that context, it could be a

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:01.130
little bit, you know, complex.

00:23:01.130 --> 00:23:04.290
So I used "traduit langue originelle anglais

00:23:04.320 --> 00:23:06.400
", translated source language English.

